[1] Brazil (Pernambuco)
Date: Fri 10 Jan 2014
Source: NE10 [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ, edited]
http://ne10.uol.com.br/canal/cotidiano/grande-recife/noticia/2014/01/10/pernambuco-em-alerta-com-aumento-de-casos-de-sarampo-em-todo-o-estado-464518.php


Pernambuco is experiencing a measles outbreak, although the Pan American Health Organization (PAHO) accredited the Brazilian territory as free of the disease in 2012. That year, there was only one confirmed case of measles in the state. In 2013, however, there were 689 notifications of suspected cases, of which 138 were officially confirmed, including the death of a 7 month old baby in the city of Moreno in the Recife Metropolitan Region (RMR). To date, there are still 230 cases under investigation; the rest were discarded.

To receive certification from PAHO, the then health minister Jose Gomes, submitted the application in 2010. The Federal Government was able to prove that vaccination coverage had reached 95 per cent of the population, in addition to proving that the last transmission of the disease within the Brazilian territory had occurred 10 years earlier, in 2000.

More than half of the cases are concentrated in RMR and areas of Mata, but there have also been reports from Caruaru (Agreste) and a suspected case from Ouricuri (Sertao) [Pernambuco]. According to public health nurse Rosilene Hans, director of State Disease Control, Recife, Cabo de Santo Agostinho, and Goiana are among the most affected municipalities [see map at http://www.slideshare.net/fullscreen/JCOnLine/mapa-sarampo-29859857/1].

The Federal Government has stated its position through the official statement that, "to ensure the interruption of transmission [of the virus], the Ministry of Health sent about 900 000 doses of MMR [measles, mumps, rubella vaccine] to Pernambuco between July and November 2013. Also in November 2013, the Ministry of Health assisted the State Secretariat of Health (SES) in implementing a vaccination campaign for children under 5 years of age in 16 priority municipalities in the state."

Health care authorities claim that the cases in Brazil have been "imported" from other countries, especially European countries such as France, where the disease has not been controlled. According to SES, cases of measles in the state increased after the Carnival [8-13 Feb 2013], when many tourists came to participate in traditional festivals. In the year of the [Association Football] World Cup [2014], the claim that tourists can "bring" measles becomes even more worrisome.

Rosilene Hans warns that "the cases that reappeared in April [2013] are of the measles virus genotype D8, very common in Europe, Asia, and Canada. The 1st cases diagnosed with the disease had had contact with individuals who traveled from these areas at risk."

Despite the justification for the resurgence of measles, a 20 year old housewife does not know how her son of 17 months may have contracted the disease. The child had a fever on a Sunday, which the family thought was a natural reaction to teething. However, on Monday, the boy had a rash, particularly on the face, coryza, conjunctivitis, and a cough. The boy's mother decided to take him to the nearest health unit where the pediatrician confirmed that the boy showed all the signs of measles. "My son had 2 doses of the vaccine (MMR) and had no contact with anyone sick. We did not travel or have contact with anyone who had traveled out of the country. I do not know how he got (measles)," says the mother. The case is not yet listed as confirmed in municipal or state records, but as a preventive measure, the city Health Department has vaccinated all persons who have had contact with the child, including the child's family and all the residents of the street where the family resides.

According to Pernambuco infectious disease and tropical medicine specialist Vera Magalhaes, "In fact, there have been some cases of measles [in Pernambuco] and in other states as well for some time, but only now is it being recognized because the disease was considered eradicated." The doctor also affirms that the supposed extinction of the disease in Brazil may have made the population careless in relation to measles. "I believe, yes, that the absence of registered cases may have made people think they were fully protected and, therefore, no longer vaccinated. So, when the disease comes back, it comes with everything," comments Magalhaes.

According to the doctor, about 30 years ago, measles was a very serious problem and a major cause of death among children under one year of age. "The return of this disease takes us back 30 years in our evolution. The warning is important because in case of complications, the victim may become blind and even die," adds the expert. Nurse Hans also states that the symptoms of measles can be mistaken, even for dengue.

[byline: Marilia Banholzer]

