[3] European Union/European Economic Area
Date: 10 Jan 2014
Source: Vaccine News Daily [edited]
http://vaccinenewsdaily.com/medical_countermeasures/329245-ecdc-reports-12096-measles-cases-in-eu-last-year/


Between November 2012 and October [2013], 12 096 cases of measles were reported by the 30 European Union/European Economic Area countries, the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control said on Tuesday [7 Jan 2014]. The ECDC released a surveillance report on Tuesday covering the 12-month period up to the end of October [2013]. The report found that despite measles and rubella being targeted for elimination in Europe by 2015, a number of countries in Europe continue to experience large measles and rubella outbreaks.

The countries reporting the most measles cases were Italy, which experienced 28 per cent of Europe's reported cases, the United Kingdom, with 19 per cent of the cases, and the Netherlands, with 18 per cent of Europe's measles cases. Germany and Romania each experienced 14 per cent of Europe's reported measles cases. Those 5 countries alone accounted for 93 per cent of all cases in Europe.

The Netherlands experienced the highest notification rate for measles, with 130 cases for each one million people. Eleven countries surveyed reported a measles notification rate of less than one case per million individuals, which is the target rate for measles elimination. The measles vaccination status was known for 9882 cases out of the 12 096 reported cases. Of these cases, 87 per cent were unvaccinated, 9 per cent received one dose of measles vaccine, 0.5 per cent received 2 or more doses, and 4 per cent received an unknown number of disease [sic; presumably "vaccines"].

There were 3 measles-related deaths reported during the period, and 8 cases were complicated by acute measles encephalitis.

During the 12-month period, 39 122 cases of rubella were reported, with Poland accounting for 99 per cent of the cases. The report found that 88 per cent of the rubella patients were either unvaccinated or had an unknown status of vaccination.

[byline: Paul Tinder]

